# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kaiser-wilhelm-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The **1903 major league baseball season** began on April 16, 1903.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Boston Americans as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the first modern World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Americans defeated the Pirates, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the return of a postseason championship series, the World Series, following the one-off 1900 *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] It was also the first inter-league series since the 1890 World's Championship Series between the National League and defunct-since-1891 American Association.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 World Series would also mark the first championship series that is still celebrated today, as all previous series are considered pre-modern and these early contests are discussed by MLB and baseball historians separately.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] However, the 1903 arrangement was primarily between the two participating clubs rather than a formal arrangement between the leagues, essentially making this season's World Series a voluntary event.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The defunct Baltimore Orioles were replaced by a new franchise in New York City known as the New York Highlanders; it was the last change to the lineup of AL and NL franchises until 1953.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would not return to Baltimore until the St.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns relocated there as a new Baltimore Orioles in 1954.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Orphans and Cleveland Bronchos were renamed as the Chicago Cubs and Cleveland Naps, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1901 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the last season with this format, as the following season would see an increase of games played.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 16 with four teams playing, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 20, with a doubleheader between the Philadelphia Athletics and the Boston Americans.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 27, while the American League would see its final day of the season on September 29.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The inaugural World Series took place between October 1 and October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (6 in AL, 9 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Americans defeating the Pittsburgh Pirates in the 1903 World Series in eight games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] Termed the "Battle of Ohio", the Cincinnati Reds and Cleveland Naps played an unofficial best of 11-game exhibition series after the regular season, with Cleveland winning the series six games to three.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The 1903 season saw the enfranchisement of the New York Highlanders, in place of the folded Baltimore Orioles, playing at Hilltop Park in New York City, New York, where they would play for ten seasons through 1912.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] On August 8, in what is known as the worst disaster in American sports spectating history, Black Saturday, a section of balcony at the Philadelphia Phillies' home at the Baker Bowl collapsed, killing 12 spectators and injuring 232.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1903-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Phillies played the last 16 of their 61 home games at the home of the American League crosstown Philadelphia Athletics, Columbia Park from August 20.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The **1904 major league baseball season** was contested from April 14 to October 10, 1904.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans and New York Giants finished atop the standings for the American League and National League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason: with still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues, the Giants declined to meet the Americans in the 1904 World Series.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the Americans were the defending World Series from the 1903 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns and Detroit Tigers played 11 consecutive games against each other in September—the first six in Detroit and the final five in St.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Louis—the most games played consecutively between two teams in major league history.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings shortened their name to the Chicago White Sox.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The 1904 schedule consisted of 154 games (an increase from 140 from the previous season) for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] This format was an adjustment to the 140-game, 20-games-each format that had been in place from the 1901 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League would see their final day of the regular season on October 9 & 10, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the New York Highlanders, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] 29 tie games (18 in AL, 11 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] With still no formal arrangement in place between the two leagues regarding the staging of the World Series, the New York Giants refused to play against the Boston Americans or any other team from what they considered an inferior league.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators leave American League Park (where they played three seasons) and move into a new American League Park, where they would go on to play seven seasons through 1910.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1904-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Highlanders play one game at Wiedenmeyer's Park in Newark, New Jersey on Sunday, July 17, as a makeup between them and the Detroit Tigers and to avoid New York City's blue laws.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The **1905 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1905.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended October 8, with the New York Giants and the Philadelphia Athletics as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the second modern World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Athletics, four games to one, capturing their first modern championship in franchise history.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Stung by criticism from fans and writers for his team's refusal to play in the previous season's World Series, Giants owner John T.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Brush drafted rules during the offseason to formally establish the World Series as a compulsory event.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Both leagues then adopted the agreement in mid-February 1905.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The 1905 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 16 with all but the Detroit Tigers and Cleveland Naps playing.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 8.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 9 and October 14.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing the Detroit Tigers, in a rescheduled game, to play at a ballpark in a different locality.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] 19 tie games (11 in AL, 8 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 14 with the New York Giants defeating the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1905 World Series in five games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators' American League Park was renamed to National Park.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1905-major-league-baseball-season] Due to horse races at main home ballpark, Bennett Park, the Detroit Tigers played two games at Neil Park in Columbus, Ohio, home of the Class A minor league Columbus Senators, on July 23 and 24.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The **1908 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1908.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 8, with the Chicago Cubs and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In a rematch of the prior year's postseason, the postseason began with Game 1 of the fifth modern World Series on October 10 and ended with Game 5 on October 14.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), The Cubs defeated the Tigers, four games to one, capturing their second championship in franchise history, and the first team to win back-to-back World Series.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Americans renamed as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The 1908 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 10 and October 14.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] 16 tie games (10 in AL, 6 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 10 and ended on October 14 with the Chicago Cubs defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1908 World Series in five games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1908-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics would play their final game at Columbia Park with a doubleheader on October 3 against the Boston Red Sox, moving into Shibe Park for the start of the 1909 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The **1910 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1910.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 15, with the Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the seventh modern World Series on October 17 and ended with Game 5 on October 23.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics defeated the Cubs, four games to one, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Pittsburgh Pirates from the 1909 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The 1910 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time, Opening Day, which took place on April 14, featured all sixteen teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on October 9, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season was on October 15.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 17 and October 23.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] 26 tie games (19 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 17 and ended on October 23 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1910 World Series in five games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their last games at the original National Park with a doubleheader on October 6 against the Boston Red Sox.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The park burned down in March 1911 and the Senators moved into a new National Park for the start of the 1911 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1910-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox would play their last game at South Side Park on June 27, having played ten seasons there going back to their inaugural 1901 season, and opened White Sox Park on July 1, where they would go on to play for 81 seasons through 1990.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The **1915 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1915.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League regular season ended on October 3, and saw the Chicago Whales winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season for the National League and American League ended on October 7, with the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 12th World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Phillies, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1912.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Braves from the 1914 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series had again featured the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, though this time with their opposite-league counterparts.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers relocated to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Buffeds, Chicago Federals, and Cleveland Naps renamed as the Buffalo Blues, Chicago Whales, and Cleveland Indians, respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League brought an antitrust lawsuit against the National and American Leagues prior to the 1915 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The parties eventually reached a settlement and the Federal League disbanded after the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The 1915 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 10, featuring all eight teams.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, featuring the 16 teams of those two leagues, as had been scheduled the season prior.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 3.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season for the National and American Leagues was October 7.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 13.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National League established that player-managers would count against the player limit, so the bench manager would be unable to insert himself in any game during the season without forfeiting the right to carry one of the players on his roster.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The penalty for violating the rule was forfeiture of the game.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (10 in AL, 13 in NL, 8 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series in five games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Indianapolis Hoosiers from Indianapolis, Indiana to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers, they leave Federal League Park and move into Harrison Park.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves would play their last game at Fenway Park on July 26, having shared the park with the Boston Red Sox since the middle of 1914, and opened Braves Field on August 18, playing their final 26 of 78 home games and where they would go on to play for 38 seasons through 1952.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs would play their final game at West Side Park on October 3 against the St.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the home of the Chicago Whales (who would fold before the 1916 season), Weeghman Park for the start of the 1916 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] For games 3 and 4 of the World Series, the Boston Red Sox use the Boston Braves home of Braves Field due to its larger capacity over their home at Fenway Park (40,000 to 27,000).
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first year in a row where a World Series winning Red Sox used Braves Field.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm held the minor league baseball pitching record for consecutive scoreless innings for 97 years, but was not recognized as the record holder by baseball officials until 2004.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Baseball officials declared Wilhelm the record holder a few days before Brad Thompson was thought to have broken the record.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Two days after Wilhelm's streak was thought to have been broken, *The New York Times* reported a historian found three scoreless innings which were previously left off Wilhelm's streak, indicating his record had not actually been broken.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm is still the current record holder.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm was born in Wooster, Ohio, to Joseph H. and Celia P.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] His father had found work as a painter, blacksmith and house decorator.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm attended Wooster High School; the school did not have a baseball team.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] He entered professional baseball in 1895 with the Mansfield Kids.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] While pitching for the Birmingham Barons in 1902, Wilhelm threw back-to-back one-hit games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] This attracted the attention of Pittsburgh Pirates owner Barney Dreyfuss, who invited Wilhelm to spring training with the Pirates in 1903.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm appeared in 12 games that year for the Pirates, finishing with a 5–3 win–loss record.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] He played with the Boston Beaneaters in the next two seasons.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In 1904, Wilhelm earned a 14–20 record and gave up a league-high 118 earned runs.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] The next year he gave up 122 earned runs, second highest in the league, and finished with a 3–23 record.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm became commonly known as "Kaiser" during his career, a nickname which originated from the early 20th century German emperor Wilhelm II.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Playing with the Barons in 1906, Wilhelm pitched the team's first perfect game since its founding in 1884.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] The 1906 Barons won the team's first title since joining the Southern Association in 1901.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] He had similar success the following year, finishing 23–14.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm returned to the major leagues with the Brooklyn Superbas from 1908 to 1910.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] His most notable game from that period may have been a three-hit, thirteen-inning win on Opening Day 1909; opposing pitcher Red Ames had a no-hitter going into the tenth inning.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In his three seasons with Brooklyn, he registered a 22–42 record.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm was back in the minor leagues with Rochester in 1911.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In three seasons with Rochester, he won 48 games and lost 24 games.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Before the 1914 baseball season, Wilhelm was signed by the Baltimore Terrapins of the Federal League (FL).
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In 1915, the new Colonial League emerged with backing from the FL.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] An agreement between the leagues provided each Colonial League team with six FL players; the FL received $200 per month for each player sent to the new league.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] When ordered to the new league by FL officials, Wilhelm refused to report.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In 1916, Wilhelm sued the Terrapins on the grounds he had signed a three-year contract in 1914 worth $10,500 and was not allowed to continue with the team after July 1, 1915.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm spent the 1916 and 1917 seasons with the Elmira Colonels of the New York State League.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In those two seasons, he finished 14–19 and 17–16 respectively.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm pitched for the Jersey City Skeeters of the International League in 1920.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] That year he was the winning pitcher of both games of a doubleheader, leading the team to 7–3 and 10–0 wins.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm became manager of the Philadelphia Phillies during the 1921 season.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In early September, *The New York Times* criticized Wilhelm's team after losing both games of a doubleheader, saying that "Every day is Labor Day for the Phillies...
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm was discharged from his position in late 1922.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm's managerial record was 83–137 in Philadelphia, which included 96 losses in 1922.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In 1923, Wilhelm made his final professional appearance as a player, taking part in a single game with the Rochester Tribe.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] He then managed the Bridgeport Bears in 1925.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In the summer of 1928, Wilhelm took a position as scout for the Montreal Royals.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Wilhelm died in 1936 and a benefit minor league game was held in Rochester to assist his widow.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] While playing in the minor leagues in 1907, Wilhelm pitched a long streak of consecutive innings without giving up a run.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] In May 2004, pitcher Brad Thompson was approaching the minor league record for this statistical category, by this time thought by the National Association of Professional Baseball Leagues (NAPBL) to belong to Urban Shocker.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Shocker threw 54 consecutive scoreless innings in 1916.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] A May 16 Associated Press article said the NAPBL took a further look at its records and recognized Wilhelm held the record, having thrown 56 consecutive scoreless innings in 1907.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] On May 19, 2004, Thompson took his streak to 57 innings before he gave up a run.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Two days after Thompson was thought to have broken the record, *The New York Times* published an article indicating three innings had been previously left off Wilhelm's scoreless innings streak, meaning Wilhelm should still hold the record for the longest such streak in the minor leagues—59 innings.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] The omitted innings had been discovered by Dave Chase, who was a baseball historian and a minor league general manager for the Memphis Redbirds.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] Baseball researcher Ray Nemec later found Wilhelm had come up to the major leagues with his streak intact, then returned to the minor leagues in 1911 and pitched 13 more consecutive scoreless innings.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] This took Wilhelm's minor league consecutive scoreless innings streak to 72.
[src:kaiser-wilhelm-baseball/kaiser-wilhelm-baseball] According to research by Walter Johnson's biographer, the actual record should be 77, from Johnson's 1907 season with the Weiser Kids of the Idaho State League.
